<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRITAIN, COWS DO THE PUNCHING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Paramedics rescued a man mauled by a herd of cows. 
</P>
<P>
 John Hine was crossing a field while walking his two golden retrievers Sunday 
near Tetsworth, 40 miles northwest of London, when the Jersey cows spotted him. 
</P>
<P>
 The cows knocked him to the ground, breaking his leg and badly bruising his 
chest. He was reported in serious but stable condition. 
</P>
<P>
 Hine was unable to move after he was knocked down and called for help on his 
cellular phone. His dogs barked to help paramedics locate their owner. 
</P>
<P>
 "There were calves in the field, so I think the cows were being protective," a 
paramedic said. "We called in the police helicopter, and when it arrived all 
the cows came over to see what was going on." 
